properties.sfomuseum:description: Airmail flight cover, first U.S. Navy Flight, San Francisco - Honolulu, August 31, 1925, accompanied by photographs and documentation (b-m); cover carried and signed by Commander John Rodgers, PN 9 No. 1; identified by donor with additional information: "Flight began August 31, forced down at sea out of fuel, drifted for nine days before taken in tow by submarine. Two official covers mailed at Honolulu, of which this is the only reported survivor."a. envelope: postmarked September 13 [year illegible], Honolulu, Hawaii, at 7:30 AM; cancellation mark on single red 2-cent stamp at upper right; addressed to Helen Hisenman; text in upper left corner: “Air Mail San Francisco to Hawaii via PN 9 No. 1”; signed by John Rodgers, Commander, U.S. Navy.b. enclosure: handwritten note addressed to Helen Hisenman from Kate [last name omitted].c. black and white photograph depicting angled rear view of flying boat U.S. Navy aircraft docked on shoreline, approached by male figures via inclined ramp.d. black and white photograph depicting distant three-quarter view of three side-by-side flying boat aircraft in motion on water.e. black and white photograph depicting five male flight crew members in frontal pose, standing on lawn in front of house.f. black and white photograph depicting five male flight crew members in frontal pose, adorned with leis, standing on lawn in front of house; figures identified on bottom margin as: Bowlin, Pope, Rodgers, Connell, and Stantz.g. black and white photograph depicting three-quarter view of flying boat aircraft 10P1 resting on water with rotating propellers; aircraft 10P2 in distance at left.h. black and white photograph depicting profile view of flying boat U.S. Navy aircraft resting on water.i-m. letter and four-page document addressed to Allyn Cole from Jack Crampon, dated October 2, 1979; contains history of John Rodgers' flight covers.
properties.wof:name: airmail flight cover: First U.S. Navy flight, San Francisco - Honolulu, August 31, 1925
